schemas.name: TrafficSplit
schemas.desc: Traffic routing configuration for versions within a single service. Traffic splits define how traffic directed to the service is assigned to versions.

fields.name: shardBy
fields.desc: Mechanism used to determine which version a request is sent to. The traffic selection algorithm will be stable for either type until allocations are changed.

enum.name: UNSPECIFIED
enum.desc: Diversion method unspecified.

enum.name: COOKIE
enum.desc: Diversion based on a specially named cookie, "GOOGAPPUID." The cookie must be set by the application itself or no diversion will occur.

enum.name: IP
enum.desc: Diversion based on applying the modulus operation to a fingerprint of the IP address.

enum.name: RANDOM
enum.desc: Diversion based on weighted random assignment. An incoming request is randomly routed to a version in the traffic split, with probability proportional to the version's traffic share.

fields.name: allocations
fields.desc: Mapping from version IDs within the service to fractional (0.000, 1] allocations of traffic for that version. Each version can be specified only once, but some versions in the service may not have any traffic allocation. Services that have traffic allocated cannot be deleted until either the service is deleted or their traffic allocation is removed. Allocations must sum to 1. Up to two decimal place precision is supported for IP-based splits and up to three decimal places is supported for cookie-based splits.

fields.name: redirectHttpResponseCode
fields.desc: 30x code to use when performing redirects for the secure field. Defaults to 302.

enum.name: REDIRECT_HTTP_RESPONSE_CODE_UNSPECIFIED

enum.name: REDIRECT_HTTP_RESPONSE_CODE_301
enum.desc: 301 Moved Permanently code.

enum.name: REDIRECT_HTTP_RESPONSE_CODE_302
enum.desc: 302 Moved Temporarily code.

enum.name: REDIRECT_HTTP_RESPONSE_CODE_303
enum.desc: 303 See Other code.

enum.name: REDIRECT_HTTP_RESPONSE_CODE_307
enum.desc: 307 Temporary Redirect code.

fields.name: securityLevel
fields.desc: Security (HTTPS) enforcement for this URL.

enum.name: SECURE_UNSPECIFIED
enum.desc: Not specified.

enum.name: SECURE_DEFAULT
enum.desc: Both HTTP and HTTPS requests with URLs that match the handler succeed without redirects. The application can examine the request to determine which protocol was used, and respond accordingly.

enum.name: SECURE_NEVER
enum.desc: Requests for a URL that match this handler that use HTTPS are automatically redirected to the HTTP equivalent URL.

enum.name: SECURE_OPTIONAL
enum.desc: Both HTTP and HTTPS requests with URLs that match the handler succeed without redirects. The application can examine the request to determine which protocol was used and respond accordingly.

enum.name: SECURE_ALWAYS
enum.desc: Requests for a URL that match this handler that do not use HTTPS are automatically redirected to the HTTPS URL with the same path. Query parameters are reserved for the redirect.

fields.name: authFailAction
fields.desc: Action to take when users access resources that require authentication. Defaults to redirect.

enum.name: AUTH_FAIL_ACTION_UNSPECIFIED
enum.desc: Not specified. AUTH_FAIL_ACTION_REDIRECT is assumed.

enum.name: AUTH_FAIL_ACTION_REDIRECT
enum.desc: Redirects user to "accounts.google.com". The user is redirected back to the application URL after signing in or creating an account.

enum.name: AUTH_FAIL_ACTION_UNAUTHORIZED
enum.desc: Rejects request with a 401 HTTP status code and an error message.

fields.name: script
fields.desc: Executes a script to handle the request that matches this URL pattern.

fields.name: urlRegex
fields.desc: URL prefix. Uses regular expression syntax, which means regexp special characters must be escaped, but should not contain groupings. All URLs that begin with this prefix are handled by this handler, using the portion of the URL after the prefix as part of the file path.

fields.name: login
fields.desc: Level of login required to access this resource.

enum.name: LOGIN_UNSPECIFIED

enum.name: LOGIN_OPTIONAL

enum.name: LOGIN_ADMIN

enum.name: LOGIN_REQUIRED
enum.desc: If the user has signed in, the handler proceeds normally. Otherwise, the auth_fail_action is taken.

fields.name: subnetworkName
fields.desc:
Google Cloud Platform sub-network where the virtual machines are created. Specify the short name, not the resource path.If a subnetwork name is specified, a network name will also be required unless it is for the default network.
If the network the VM instance is being created in is a Legacy network, then the IP address is allocated from the IPv4Range.
If the network the VM instance is being created in is an auto Subnet Mode Network, then only network name should be specified (not the subnetwork_name) and the IP address is created from the IPCidrRange of the subnetwork that exists in that zone for that network.
If the network the VM instance is being created in is a custom Subnet Mode Network, then the subnetwork_name must be specified and the IP address is created from the IPCidrRange of the subnetwork.If specified, the subnetwork must exist in the same region as the Flex app.

schemas.name: Operation
schemas.desc: This resource represents a long-running operation that is the result of a network API call.

fields.name: metadata
fields.desc: Service-specific metadata associated with the operation. It typically contains progress information and common metadata such as create time. Some services might not provide such metadata. Any method that returns a long-running operation should document the metadata type, if any.

fields.name: done
fields.desc: If the value is false, it means the operation is still in progress. If true, the operation is completed, and either error or response is available.

fields.name: response
fields.desc: The normal response of the operation in case of success. If the original method returns no data on success, such as Delete, the response is google.protobuf.Empty. If the original method is standard Get/Create/Update, the response should be the resource. For other methods, the response should have the type XxxResponse, where Xxx is the original method name. For example, if the original method name is TakeSnapshot(), the inferred response type is TakeSnapshotResponse.

fields.name: name
fields.desc: The server-assigned name, which is only unique within the same service that originally returns it. If you use the default HTTP mapping, the name should have the format of operations/some/unique/name.

fields.name: error

schemas.name: Status
schemas.desc:
The Status type defines a logical error model that is suitable for different programming environments, including REST APIs and RPC APIs. It is used by gRPC (https://github.com/grpc). The error model is designed to be:
Simple to use and understand for most users
Flexible enough to meet unexpected needsOverviewThe Status message contains three pieces of data: error code, error message, and error details. The error code should be an enum value of google.rpc.Code, but it may accept additional error codes if needed. The error message should be a developer-facing English message that helps developers understand and resolve the error. If a localized user-facing error message is needed, put the localized message in the error details or localize it in the client. The optional error details may contain arbitrary information about the error. There is a predefined set of error detail types in the package google.rpc which can be used for common error conditions.Language mappingThe Status message is the logical representation of the error model, but it is not necessarily the actual wire format. When the Status message is exposed in different client libraries and different wire protocols, it can be mapped differently. For example, it will likely be mapped to some exceptions in Java, but more likely mapped to some error codes in C.Other usesThe error model and the Status message can be used in a variety of environments, either with or without APIs, to provide a consistent developer experience across different environments.Example uses of this error model include:
Partial errors. If a service needs to return partial errors to the client, it may embed the Status in the normal response to indicate the partial errors.
Workflow errors. A typical workflow has multiple steps. Each step may have a Status message for error reporting purpose.
Batch operations. If a client uses batch request and batch response, the Status message should be used directly inside batch response, one for each error sub-response.
Asynchronous operations. If an API call embeds asynchronous operation results in its response, the status of those operations should be represented directly using the Status message.
Logging. If some API errors are stored in logs, the message Status could be used directly after any stripping needed for security/privacy reasons.

fields.name: message
fields.desc: A developer-facing error message, which should be in English. Any user-facing error message should be localized and sent in the google.rpc.Status.details field, or localized by the client.

fields.name: details
fields.desc: A list of messages that carry the error details. There will be a common set of message types for APIs to use.

fields.name: code
fields.desc: The status code, which should be an enum value of google.rpc.Code.

Each service has a collection of versions that define a specific set of code used to implement the functionality of that service.

enum.name: STOPPED

schemas.name: ApiConfigHandler
schemas.desc: Google Cloud Endpoints (https://cloud.google.com/appengine/docs/python/endpoints/) configuration for API handlers.

fields.name: url
fields.desc: URL to serve the endpoint at.

fields.name: securityLevel
fields.desc: Security (HTTPS) enforcement for this URL.

enum.name: SECURE_UNSPECIFIED
enum.desc: Not specified.

enum.name: SECURE_DEFAULT
enum.desc: Both HTTP and HTTPS requests with URLs that match the handler succeed without redirects. The application can examine the request to determine which protocol was used, and respond accordingly.

enum.name: SECURE_NEVER
enum.desc: Requests for a URL that match this handler that use HTTPS are automatically redirected to the HTTP equivalent URL.

enum.name: SECURE_OPTIONAL
enum.desc: Both HTTP and HTTPS requests with URLs that match the handler succeed without redirects. The application can examine the request to determine which protocol was used and respond accordingly.

enum.name: SECURE_ALWAYS
enum.desc: Requests for a URL that match this handler that do not use HTTPS are automatically redirected to the HTTPS URL with the same path. Query parameters are reserved for the redirect.

fields.name: authFailAction
fields.desc: Action to take when users access resources that require authentication. Defaults to redirect.

enum.name: AUTH_FAIL_ACTION_UNSPECIFIED
enum.desc: Not specified. AUTH_FAIL_ACTION_REDIRECT is assumed.

enum.name: AUTH_FAIL_ACTION_REDIRECT
enum.desc: Redirects user to "accounts.google.com". The user is redirected back to the application URL after signing in or creating an account.

enum.name: AUTH_FAIL_ACTION_UNAUTHORIZED
enum.desc: Rejects request with a 401 HTTP status code and an error message.

fields.name: script
fields.desc: Path to the script from the application root directory.

fields.name: login
fields.desc: Level of login required to access this resource. Defaults to optional.

enum.name: LOGIN_UNSPECIFIED
enum.desc: Not specified. LOGIN_OPTIONAL is assumed.

enum.name: LOGIN_OPTIONAL
enum.desc: Does not require that the user is signed in.

enum.name: LOGIN_ADMIN
enum.desc: If the user is not signed in, the auth_fail_action is taken. In addition, if the user is not an administrator for the application, they are given an error message regardless of auth_fail_action. If the user is an administrator, the handler proceeds.

enum.name: LOGIN_REQUIRED
enum.desc: If the user has signed in, the handler proceeds normally. Otherwise, the auth_fail_action is taken.

schemas.name: StaticFilesHandler
schemas.desc: Files served directly to the user for a given URL, such as images, CSS stylesheets, or JavaScript source files. Static file handlers describe which files in the application directory are static files, and which URLs serve them.

fields.name: expiration
fields.desc: Time a static file served by this handler should be cached by web proxies and browsers.

fields.name: httpHeaders
fields.desc: HTTP headers to use for all responses from these URLs.

fields.name: applicationReadable
fields.desc: Whether files should also be uploaded as code data. By default, files declared in static file handlers are uploaded as static data and are only served to end users; they cannot be read by the application. If enabled, uploads are charged against both your code and static data storage resource quotas.

fields.name: uploadPathRegex
fields.desc: Regular expression that matches the file paths for all files that should be referenced by this handler.

fields.name: path
fields.desc: Path to the static files matched by the URL pattern, from the application root directory. The path can refer to text matched in groupings in the URL pattern.

fields.name: mimeType
fields.desc: MIME type used to serve all files served by this handler.Defaults to file-specific MIME types, which are derived from each file's filename extension.

fields.name: requireMatchingFile
fields.desc: Whether this handler should match the request if the file referenced by the handler does not exist.
